11/13/2022

InSpace Geocoding Protocol

Important NOTE: Do not put any participant addresses or streets into google maps. Google is a third party and doing so shares identifiable participant information with google

Ensuring the most precise geocoding of participant addresses will enable you to pull the most accurate measures of the environmental context. While the ACMT has a built-in geocoder, we also rely on our partners to verify that the geocodes produced by the ACMT accurately represent the location of each participant.

Cleaning up addresses and checking geocodes may benefit from local knowledge of the area in which your participants reside. If you are not familiar with your local area, it may be helpful to talk to someone else in your lab (someone who is on the IRB for your project) to identify potential address and/or geocoding errors.

The process of verifying participant locations is an iterative process of mapping geocodes, updating addresses, re-mapping, and noting where location are inaccurate, even after address updates. This process utilizes the ACMT map checking and geocoder functions to produce maps, geocodes, and ratings of the geocodes. The open source map that the ACMT utilizes is limited in some contexts, which may impede your ability to precisely see the street name or specific location of the mapped address. When you are unable to improve the geocode rating or verify the accuracy of the geocoded location, please make a note. (for example: Unable to determine the accuracy of the geocode, no street name)

This tool may also be helpful in verifying zip codes in your area: https://www.unitedstateszipcodes.org/

Import address data & combine address fields if necessary

  • You will first need to upload your datatset into your Inspace folder, import your data into the R environment, and update using the provided code so that your data is formatted as follows, with an id field with the record id and an address field with the full address:
id address
5 1245 First Ave, Seattle, WA, 98564
18 6789 Second Street, Seattle, WA, 98564
89 999 MLK Way, Seattle, WA, 98564
.. .

Run Mapping function loop to map all addresses

Next, use the code provided in the Mapping Geocodes - Code file to geocode the addresses to get the lat / long values for each individual in the dataset.

The provided code will create two documents for you to reference as you check the geocode locations: (1) A pdf file with a map printed for each individual in your dataset (2) A csv file with ratings, address, and a notes columns.

Youll find these documents in your Inspace folder after running the code in Step 3 of the Mapping Geocodes document. Export them and use them to review the maps.

Running the geocode loop will also produce a table of your initial geocode ratings. This will give you a sense of how many addresses will require follow-up review (i.e., all ratings >0)

Check geocodes wit high ratings

  • Once you have geocoded your data and exported the dataset_address_check document, open the file in excel. You can work off of this file as you check geolocations and make notes about addresses that have high ratings, but look accurate.

For each address with rating >10, take the following steps: NOTE: Do not put any participant addresses into google maps. We recommend you rely solely on the ACMT mapper for this step to avoid inappropriate sharing of participant data

NOTE: your exported dataset with addresses and ratings will be sorted by rating, starting with the highest rating. While we want to you to check all addresses with >0 rating, prioritize those with the highest rating, and spend the least amount of time on those with 1-10 ratings. Comment on all geocodes that still have ratings >10 after updates.

  1. Update the address to write out any Ave to Avenue, S to South, etc.
  2. Check the zip code for the given city and/or cross street. This website: https://www.unitedstateszipcodes.org/ is a helpful tool for locating zip codes in your area.
  3. Use the ACMT to map the geocode (using the settings to adjust zoom and detail level) to help confirm whether the geocode is accurate (getting help from a teammate who is familiar with the area may be beneficial here).
  4. If the geocode is >0 but is mapping to the correct location, make a comment in the notes column.
  5. If you are unsure if the location is correct or not based off of the map, and the rating is still >10 after edits, make a comment in the notes column (i.e., unable to verify address based on map, cannot improve the address) and move on to the next address.

After each step, you can use the code below to make the updates to the dataset directly in R and to re-geocode and re-map the updated location. Use the z value and the side_len values and update to increase/decrease the detail or the zoom level of the map (helpful if some or all tiles of the map are missing)

## enter the id number for the participant whose address you are updating here: 
i<- 30 #
## enter the updated address text for the individual here:  
update.address<- '2692 State Route 903, Cle Elum, WA, 98922' 
## change the level of detail of the map: 
z<-15# #higher numbers here give more detailed maps, but may not be available for more rural areas - you can lower the number to 14 or 15 if the map is blank. 
## change the zoom level of the map: 
side_len<-0.007 # higher numbers give a larger map, but may take longer to load (I recommend not going higher than 0.05)


#update the address in the dataset for the given id
dataset_geocode$address[dataset_geocode$id==i]<-update.address
dataset_geocode$address[dataset_geocode$id==i]
## [1] "2692 State Route 903, Cle Elum, WA, 98922"
## get updated geocodes and put the updated geocode and rating into the dataset:
address<-dataset_geocode$address[dataset_geocode$id==i]
lat_long<-tryCatch({geocode(address)}, 
                     error=function(x){
                       lat_long<-list(latitude=NA, longitude=NA, rating=NA)
                       })
  dataset_geocode$lat[dataset_geocode$id==i]<-lat_long$latitude # add latitude to dataset_geocode
  dataset_geocode$long[dataset_geocode$id==i] <-lat_long$longitude # add longitude to dataset_geocode
  dataset_geocode$rating[dataset_geocode$id==i]<-lat_long$rating # add rating to the dataset_geocode


## reprint the updated geocode
check_geocode(lat=dataset_geocode$lat[dataset_geocode$id==i], long=dataset_geocode$long[dataset_geocode$id==i], address=dataset_geocode$address[dataset_geocode$id==i], rate=dataset_geocode$rating[dataset_geocode$id==i], id=i, 
              z=z, ##higher numbers here give more detailed maps, but may not be available for more rural areas - you can lower the number to 14 or 15 if the map is blank. 
              side_len=side_len # higher numbers give a larger map, but may take longer to load (I recommend not going higher than 0.05)
              )

## if the reprinted map still looks incorrect, make additional edits to the address and rerun the code.

Export final geocoded dataset to Inspace folder

Once each address has been checked and updates have been made as needed, export your final geocoded dataset to your Inspace folder. This is the dataset that will be used for pulling environmental measures.

In the dataset_address_check.csv file, remove the address column, and save the excel file with your notes. This will be shared with the Inspace team so they can reference it for geocodes with high ratings.
